      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency when the candidate error rate e is within a plurality-collapse window 1/(k+1) > e > 1/(2k) for odd k≥7 AND the critic achieves precision P > 0.5 and recall R > 1-e on the subset of pools exhibiting vote dispersion across ≥3 distinct answers. Under these conditions, the critic breaks tied-plurality incorrect pools more often than tied-plurality correct pools, yielding net positive benefit.\", \"mechanism\": \"At lower error rates e < 1/(k+1), SC majority margins are wide, but plurality fragmentation emerges: the correct answer leads a fragmented field while dissenting votes scatter across multiple distractors. The critic functions as a dispersion-resolving classifier on tied-plurality pools. The expected net benefit = R·P_inc·N_inc - FPR·P_cor·N_cor, where P_inc is the fraction of dispersed pools that are incorrect, P_cor is the fraction that are correct. Near e = 1/(2k) for k=7, P_inc ≈ 0.34, P_cor ≈ 0.66. For net benefit > 0: R·0.34 > (1-P)·0.66. Simplifying: if R > 1-e and P > 0.5, the critic’s ability to consolidate scattered dissent favors breaking incorrect pluralities, guaranteeing net benefit on the dispersed subset.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"odd k ≥ 7\", \"e ∈ (1/(2k), 1/(k+1))\", \"P > 0.5 AND R > 1-e on dispersed-plurality subset\", \"binary-answer questions only\"], \"excludes\": [\"k ≤ 5\", \"e ≥ 1/(k+1) (SC robust majority)\", \"e ≤ 1/(2k) (uniform random noise floor)\", \"P ≤ 0.5 (critic no better than chance)\", \"multi-answer questions where plurality ≠ majority\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=7, e≈0.12, P>0.5, R>0.88: harness - SC ≤ 0 across all tested sub-bands\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Net fixed-minus-broken ≤ 0 when P > 0.5 and R > 1-e on the dispersed-plurality subset\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Harness improvement is uncorrelated with the fraction of dispersed-plurality pools in the sample (Spearman ρ < 0.3, p > 0.05)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This candidate shifts the regime of interest from fragile majorities to plurality dispersion. P > 0.5 and R > 1-e are necessary AND sufficient because they guarantee the critic can distinguish correct consolidation from incorrect fragmentation. The experiment should use a difficulty-targeted question set (not random sampling) to ensure enough questions fall in the e ≈ 1/(2k) band. With 200 questions at k=7 (1400 candidate calls + 200 critic calls + 200 SC calls ≈ 1800 calls), this fits within 300k tokens if questions are concise.\"}",
