      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency when the candidate error rate e is within a near-uniform regime 1/(k-2) > e > 1/k for odd k≥7 AND the critic achieves precision P > 2e and recall R > 1-2e on the subset of pools where vote entropy exceeds log(k-2). Under these conditions, the critic filters high-entropy incorrect majorities more often than high-entropy correct majorities, yielding net positive benefit.\", \"mechanism\": \"Let H_max = log(k) be the maximum vote entropy. At error rate e near 1/n, the probability of high-entropy majorities is maximized. The critic acts as an entropy-gated classifier on these pools. The expected net benefit = R·P_inc·N_inc - FPR·P_cor·N_cor, where P_inc = fraction of high-entropy pools that are incorrect, P_cor = fraction that are correct. Near e = 1/k for k=7, P_inc ≈ 0.38, P_cor ≈ 0.62. For net benefit > 0: R·0.38 > (1-P)·0.62. Simplifying: if R > 1-2e and P > 2e, the critic’s precision offsets the base rate of incorrect high-entropy outcomes, guaranteeing net benefit on the high-entropy subset.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"odd k ≥ 7\", \"e ∈ (1/k, 1/(k-2))\", \"P > 2e AND R > 1-2e on high-entropy subset\", \"binary-answer questions only\"], \"excludes\": [\"k ≤ 5\", \"e ≤ 1/k (deterministic regime)\", \"e ≥ 1/(k-2) (uniform random regime)\", \"P ≤ 2e (critic no better than chance)\", \"multi-answer questions where plurality ≠ majority\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=7, e≈0.17, P>0.34, R>0.66: harness - SC ≤ 0 across all tested sub-bands\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Net fixed-minus-broken ≤ 0 when P > 2e and R > 1-2e on the high-entropy subset\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Harness improvement is uncorrelated with the fraction of high-entropy pools in the sample (Spearman ρ < 0.3, p > 0.05)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This candidate uses entropy thresholds instead of margin thresholds. P > 2e and R > 1-2e are necessary AND sufficient because they guarantee the critic’s precision scales with the noise floor. The experiment should use a difficulty-targeted question set (not random sampling) to ensure enough questions fall in the e ≈ 1/k band. With 200 questions at k=7 (1400 candidate calls + 200 critic calls + 200 SC calls ≈ 1800 calls), this fits within 300k tokens if questions are concise.\"}",
